724870f-a.title: Manhattan: York Avenue - 64th Street
724870f-a.text:
york Ave., at the N.E. corner of 64th Street, shoing several of the building's comprising the Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research. LUnder the present organizations the departments maintained are: Pathology, Bacteriology, Physical and Pathological Chemistry, Physiology. comparative 2oology, Pharmacology and experimental Therapeutics. It co-operates with many other bodies in practical investigation. A hospital under the direction of the Institute is maintained where the different diseases that effect mankind are given closest scientific study.
About 1922.
Ewing Galloway.

724873f-a.title: Manhattan: York Avenue - 64th Street
724873f-a.text:
York Avenue, west side, o4th to 65th Streets, inclusive, seen from east of York Avenue, the clearing left by demolition of the old malting
plant of George Ehret.
The building for private patients, on the S.W. corner of 64th Street, is the newer pat (around 190E) of the Flower Hospital. The apartment buildings from o4th to o5th Streets were built aound
1905 where a lumber yard and a stone yard used to be.
December 22, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.

724875f-a.title: Manhattan: York Avenue - 64th Street
724875f-a.text:
york Avenue, from 64th to u7th Streets, seen from 63rd Street east of York Avenue. The clearing in the foreground, whee the Ehret malting plant has just been demolished, will be seeded with grass and fenced around; and o4th Street east of York Avenue, where the
truck is seen, will be permanently closed.
On the west side may be seen 429 Eaat o4th Street and 430 East 65th Street, built arounc 1905, 1215-29 York Avenue, from 65th to 6eth Streets, built around 1927, and 1233-35-37-39-41 Avenue A (now York Avenue) from otth to 67th Streets. The trees east of the Avenue above b4th Street are on the grounds of the Rockefeller
Institute, which accuired the property about 1902.
December 22, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.

724874f-a.title: Manhattan: York Avenue - 64th Street
724874f-a.text:
Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research, east of York Avenue from 64th to 67th Streets, not showing the power plant at 64th Street
and Marie Curie Avenue (formerly Exterior Street).
Rockefeller Institute was incorporated in 1901. The old laboratory, shown in the center, with its long axis north and south, was dedicated May 11, 1906. The Main Hospital, on the right, was built around 1910 or a little earlier. Immediately north of the old laboratory is Laboratory No. 2, which is shown in the view of York Avenue frow 63rd Street and north, early 191b. Above No. 2 and at right angles
to it is the newest laboratory, built in 1930.
June 30, 1931.
P. L. Sperr.

724871f-a.title: Manhattan: York Avenue - 64th Street (East)
724871f-a.text:
York Ave. (left), east side, north from but not including East 64th Street, showing the grounds and buildings (right foreground to center) of the Rockefeller IInstitute for Medical Research as they extend north, to East 68th Street and east,to Marie Curie Ave.; and (at the northern extremity of the wooded grounds) New York Hospital and Cornell Medical College, extending from East 68th to East 71st Streets, and east to
Marie Curie Ave.
1936.
W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Writers Project.

724872f-a.title: Manhattan: York Avenue - 64th Street (East)
724872f-a.text:
York Avenue, at the S.W. corner of East 64th Street, showing a final view of the private pavillion of the former Flower Hospital preparatory to demolition. The institutional buildings are being razed at the left. Tastructional and hospitalization activities of the New York Homoepathic College will continue at the Fifth
Avenue Hospital.
April 28, 1940
Gift of George Jiranek
Photostat Division
New York Public Library

724869f-a.title: Manhattan: York Avenue - 64th Street
724869f-a.text:
(1)
York Ave. at the S.E. corner of 64th Street, with the Queensboro Bridge in the right background. The old malting plant of George Ehret, once the American Malting Company, is being demolished. The foot of 64th Street as here shown is the beginning of Exterior Street (name changed in 1935 to Marie Curie Ave.). After the demolition of the brewery Exterior Street will be extended down to 63rd Street, and the plot fenced off, closing this block of 64th
Street.
October 20, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same, showing more of the bridge and the Park on Marie
Curie Ave.
July 31, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.
